# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flexray
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Electronic systems have become an increasingly large component of the cost of an automobile, from only around 1% of its value in 1950 to around 30% in 2010.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Modern electric cars rely on power electronics for the main propulsion motor control, as well as managing the battery system.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Future autonomous cars will rely on powerful computer systems, an array of sensors, networking, and satellite navigation, all of which will require electronics.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The earliest electronic systems available as factory installations were vacuum tube car radios, starting in the early 1930s.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The development of semiconductors after World War II greatly expanded the use of electronics in automobiles, with solid-state diodes making the automotive alternator the standard after about 1960, and the first transistorized ignition systems appearing in 1963.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The emergence of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology led to the development of modern automotive electronics.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Dawon Kahng summarized in a Bell Labs memo the achievement: E.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Ligenza who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] This led to the development of the power MOSFET by Hitachi in 1969, and the single-chip microprocessor by Federico Faggin, Marcian Hoff, Masatoshi Shima and Stanley Mazor at Intel in 1971.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The development of MOS integrated circuit (MOS IC) chips and microprocessors made a range of automotive applications economically feasible in the 1970s.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] In the early 1970s, the Japanese electronics industry began producing integrated circuits and microcontrollers for the Japanese automobile industry, used for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, dashboard, and engine control.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The Ford EEC (Electronic Engine Control) system, which utilized the Toshiba TLCS-12 PMOS microprocessor, went into mass production in 1975.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] In 1978, the Cadillac Seville featured a "trip computer" based on a 6802 microprocessor.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Electronically-controlled ignition and fuel injection systems allowed automotive designers to achieve vehicles meeting requirements for fuel economy and lower emissions, while still maintaining high levels of performance and convenience for drivers.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Today's automobiles contain a dozen or more processors, in functions such as engine management, transmission control, climate control, antilock braking, passive safety systems, navigation, and other functions.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The power MOSFET and the microcontroller, a type of single-chip microcomputer, led to significant advances in electric vehicle technology.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] MOSFET power converters allowed operation at much higher switching frequencies, made it easier to drive, reduced power losses, and significantly reduced prices, while single-chip microcontrollers could manage all aspects of the drive control and had the capacity for battery management.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used in vehicles such as automobiles, cars, trucks, electric vehicles, and smart cars.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used for the electronic control unit (ECU), while the power MOSFET and IGBT are used as the load drivers for automotive loads such as motors, solenoids, ignition coils, relays, heaters and lamps.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] In 2000, the average mid-range passenger vehicle had an estimated $100–200 of power semiconductor content, increasing by a potential 3–5 times for electric and hybrid vehicles.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] As of 2017, the average vehicle has over 50 actuators, typically controlled by power MOSFETs or other power semiconductor devices.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Another important technology that enabled modern highway-capable electric cars is the lithium-ion battery.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] It was invented by John Goodenough, Rachid Yazami and Akira Yoshino in the 1980s, and commercialized by Sony and Asahi Kasei in 1991.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The lithium-ion battery was responsible for the development of electric vehicles capable of long-distance travel, by the 2000s.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] On average, a 2020s car has 50–150 chips, according to Chris Isidore of CNN Business.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] One of the most demanding electronic parts of an automobile is the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Engine controls demand one of the highest real-time deadlines, as the engine itself is a very fast and complex part of the automobile.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Of all the electronics in any car, the computing power of the engine control unit is the highest, typically a 32-bit processor.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] A modern car may have up to 100 ECU's and a commercial vehicle up to 40.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Many more engine parameters are actively monitored and controlled in real-time.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 50 that measure pressure, temperature, flow, engine speed, oxygen level and NOx level plus other parameters at different points within the engine.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] All these sensor signals are sent to the ECU, which has the logic circuits to do the actual controlling.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The ECU output is connected to different actuators for the throttle valve, EGR valve, rack (in VGTs), fuel injector (using a pulse-width modulated signal), dosing injector and more.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 30 actuators in all.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] These control the transmission system, mainly the shifting of the gears for better shift comfort and to lower torque interrupt while shifting.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Automatic transmissions use controls for their operation, and also many semi-automatic transmissions having a fully automatic clutch or a semi-auto clutch (declutching only).
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The engine control unit and the transmission control exchange messages, sensor signals and control signals for their operation.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] All of the above systems form an infotainment system.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Developmental methods for these systems vary according to each manufacturer.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Different tools are used for both hardware and software development.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] These are new generation hybrid ECUs that combine the functionalities of multiple ECUs of Infotainment Head Unit, Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS), Instrument Cluster, Rear Camera/Parking Assist, Surround View Systems etc.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] This saves on the cost of electronics as well as mechanical/physical parts like interconnects across ECUs etc.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] There is also a more centralized control so data can be seamlessly exchanged between the systems.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Given the complexity of this hybrid system, a lot more rigor is needed to validate the system for robustness, safety and security.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] For example, if the infotainment system's application which could be running an open-source Android OS is breached, there could be possibility of hackers to take control of the car remotely and potentially misuse it for anti-social activities.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Typically so, usage of a hardware+software enabled hypervisors are used to virtualize and create separate trust and safety zones that are immune to each other's failures or breaches.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Lot of work is happening in this area and potentially will have such systems soon if not already.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] In order to minimize the risk of dangerous failures, safety-related electronic systems have to be developed following the applicable product liability requirements.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Disregard for, or inadequate application of these standards can lead to not only personal injuries, but also severe legal and economic consequences such as product cancellations or recalls.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The IEC 61508 standard, generally applicable to electrical/electronic/programmable safety-related products, is only partially adequate for automotive-development requirements.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Consequently, for the automotive industry, this standard is replaced by the existing ISO 26262, currently released as a Final Draft International Standard (FDIS).
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] ISO/DIS 26262 describes the entire product life-cycle of safety-related electrical/electronic systems for road vehicles.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] It has been published as an international standard in its final version in November 2011.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The implementation of this new standard will result in modifications and various innovations in the automobile electronics development process, as it covers the complete product life-cycle from the concept phase until its decommissioning.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] As more functions of the automobile are connected to short- or long-range networks, cybersecurity of systems against unauthorized modification is required.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] With critical systems such as engine controls, transmission, airbags, and braking connected to internal diagnostic networks, remote access could result in a malicious intruder altering the function of systems or disabling them, possibly causing injuries or fatalities.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Every new interface presents a new "attack surface".
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] The same facility that allows the owner to unlock and start a car from a smartphone app also presents risks due to remote access.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Auto manufacturers may protect the memory of various control microprocessors both to secure them from unauthorized changes and also to ensure only manufacturer-authorized facilities can diagnose or repair the vehicle.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] Systems such as keyless entry rely on cryptographic techniques to ensure "replay" or "man-in-the-middle attacks" attacks cannot record sequences to allow later break-in to the automobile.
[src:flexray/automotive-electronics] In 2015 the German general automobile club commissioned an investigation of the vulnerabilities of one manufacturer's electronics system, which could have led to such exploits as unauthorized remote unlocking of the vehicle.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Driver input is traditionally transferred to the motor, wheels, and brakes through a mechanical linkage attached to controls such as a steering wheel, throttle pedal, hydraulic brake pedal, brake pull handle, and so on, which apply mechanical forces.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] In drive-by-wire systems, driver input does not directly adjust a mechanical linkage, instead the input is processed by an electronic control unit which controls the vehicle using electromechanical actuators.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] The human–machine interface, such as a steering wheel, yoke, accelerator pedal, brake pedal, and so on, may include haptic feedback that simulates the resistance of hydraulic and mechanical pedals and steering, including steering kickback.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Components such as the steering column, intermediate shafts, pumps, hoses, belts, coolers, vacuum servos and master cylinders are eliminated from the vehicle.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Safety standards for drive-by-wire are specified by the ISO 26262 standard level D.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Because driver inputs can be overridden, safety can be improved by providing computer controlled intervention of vehicle controls with systems such as electronic stability control (ESC), adaptive cruise control and lane assist systems.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Each drive-by-wire system leads to more actuators in the vehicle and therefore greater energy consumption.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] For instance, the drive-by-wire technology adds actuator motors to create the torque needed to turn the wheels, and a feedback transducer to create the "road feel" on the steering wheel.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Safety considerations require redundancy of driver input sensors, vehicle communication networks, actuators, and other systems.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Automotive safety standards such as ISO 26262 require drive-by-wire fail-operational and fail-safe behaviors.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Failures in drive by wire systems can lead to potential hazardous situations where safety depends entirely on the vehicle's failure mode.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] The Aachen University Institute for Motor Vehicles (ika – Institut für Kraftfahrzeuge Aachen), in collaboration with Mercedes-AMG and others, studies the operation, risks, and safety mechanisms of drive-by-wire systems through its drive-by-wire concept vehicle, SpeedE.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Studied scenarios include loss of control over acceleration, brakes, or steering.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Early by-wire systems had mechanical backup systems in case the by-wire systems failed.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Such fail-safes are specified by the ISO 26262 standard level D.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Assessment and standardization of drive-by-wire computer security has also taken place.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Researchers demonstrated in 2011 and 2013 that some systems in commercially available vehicles are susceptible to hacking, allowing for external control of the vehicle.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Hacking demonstrations included remote activation of systems like the horn, windshield wipers, accelerator, brakes, and transmission.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Modern standards such as the ISO/SAE 21434 standard and UNCE regulations 155, 156, and 157 require dedicated cryptographic modules that encrypt all communication between the ECUs and the drive system components.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] A brake-by-wire system eliminates the need for a mechanical connection that transfers force between the brakes and a driver input apparatus such as a pedal or lever.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Shift-by-wire employs electrical or electronic connections that replace the mechanical connection between the driver's gearshift mechanism and the transmission.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Since becoming commercially available in 1996, shift-by-wire has been commonly used in automated manual transmission, and has later been implemented in semi-automatic transmission and automatic transmission.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Park by wire may be considered a form of shift-by-wire.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Not to be confused with park-brake by wire which engages a parking brake, park-by-wire engages the parking pawl.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] A parking pawl in a traditional automatic transmission has a mechanical link to the gear stick and locks the transmission in the park position when the gear-shift handle is set in "park".
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] A park-by-wire system uses electronic commands sent to an actuator that engages the parking pawl.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] A vehicle equipped with a steer-by-wire system is able to steer some or all of its wheels without a steering column connected to the wheel axles.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] It is different from electric power steering or power-assist, as those systems still rely on the steering column to mechanically transfer some steering torque to the wheels.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] A vehicle with a steer-by-wire system may be manually controlled by a driver through a steering wheel, a yoke, or any other steering apparatus which is connected to one or more electronic control units, which uses the input to control steering actuators that turn the wheels and steer the vehicle.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] The steering wheel or yoke may be equipped with haptic feedback to simulate road feel and wheel resistance, and change depending on the vehicle speed or customizable settings.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] Accelerate-by-wire or throttle-by-wire, more commonly known as electronic throttle control, is a system that actuates vehicle propulsion without any mechanical connections, such as cables, from the accelerator pedal to the throttle valve of the engine or other propulsion systems.
[src:flexray/drive-by-wire] In electric vehicles, this system controls the electric motors by sensing the accelerator pedal input and sending commands to the power inverter modules.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] An **electronic control unit** (**ECU**), also known as an **electronic control module** (**ECM**), is an embedded system in automotive electronics that controls one or more of the electrical systems or subsystems in a car or other motor vehicle.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] These ECUs together are sometimes referred to collectively as **the car's computer** though technically they are all separate computers, not a single one.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] Sometimes an assembly incorporates several individual control modules (a PCM often controls both the engine and the transmission).
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] Some modern motor vehicles have up to 150 ECUs.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] Embedded software in ECUs continues to increase in line count, complexity, and sophistication.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] Managing the increasing complexity and number of ECUs in a vehicle has become a key challenge for original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] The development of an ECU involves both hardware and software required to perform the functions expected from that particular module.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] Automotive ECU's are being developed following the V-model.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] Recently the trend is to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort to develop safe modules by following standards like ISO 26262.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] It is rare that a module is developed fully from scratch.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] The design is generally iterative and improvements are made to both the hardware and software.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] The development of most ECUs is carried out by Tier 1 suppliers based on specifications provided by the OEM.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] As part of the development cycle, manufacturers perform detailed FMEAs and other failure analyses to catch failure modes that can lead to unsafe conditions or driver annoyance.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] Extensive testing and validation activities are carried out as part of the production part approval process to gain the confidence of the hardware and software.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] On-board diagnostics or OBD help provide specific data related to which system or component failed or caused a failure during run time and help perform repairs.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] Some people may wish to modify their ECU so as to be able to add or change functionality.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] However modern ECUs come equipped with protection locks to prevent users from modifying the circuit or exchange chips.
[src:flexray/electronic-control-unit] The protection locks are a form of digital rights management (DRM), the circumventing of which is illegal in certain jurisdictions.
[src:flexray/flexray] FlexRay is a communication bus designed to ensure high data rates, fault tolerance, operating on a time cycle, split into static and dynamic segments for event-triggered and time-triggered communications.
[src:flexray/flexray] It is mainly used in aeronautic and automotive sectors.
[src:flexray/flexray] FlexRay supports data rates up to 10 Mbit/s, explicitly supports both star and bus physical topologies, and can have two independent data channels for fault-tolerance (communication can continue with reduced bandwidth if one channel is inoperative).
[src:flexray/flexray] The bus operates on a time cycle, divided into two parts: the static segment and the dynamic segment.
[src:flexray/flexray] The static segment is preallocated into slices for individual communication types, providing stronger determinism than its predecessor CAN.
[src:flexray/flexray] The dynamic segment operates more like CAN, with nodes taking control of the bus as available, allowing event-triggered behavior.
[src:flexray/flexray] There were also Premium Associate and Associate members of FlexRay consortium.
[src:flexray/flexray] By September 2009, there were 28 premium associate members and more than 60 associate members.
[src:flexray/flexray] At the end of 2009, the consortium disbanded.
[src:flexray/flexray] The first series production vehicle with FlexRay was at the end of 2006 in the BMW X5 (E70), enabling a new and fast adaptive damping system.
[src:flexray/flexray] Full use of FlexRay was introduced in 2008 in the new BMW 7 Series (F01).
[src:flexray/flexray] The FlexRay system consists of a bus and electronic control units (ECUs).
[src:flexray/flexray] The clock drift must be not more than 0.15% from the reference clock, so the difference between the slowest and the fastest clock in the system is no greater than 0.3%.
[src:flexray/flexray] This means that, if ECU-s is a sender and ECU-r is a receiver, then for every 300 cycles of the sender there will be between 299 and 301 cycles of the receiver.
[src:flexray/flexray] The clocks are resynchronized frequently enough to assure that this causes no problems.
[src:flexray/flexray] The clock is sent in the static segment.
[src:flexray/flexray] At each time, only one ECU writes to the bus.
[src:flexray/flexray] Each bit to be sent is held on the bus for 8 sample clock cycles.
[src:flexray/flexray] The receiver keeps a buffer of the last 5 samples, and uses the majority of the last 5 samples as the input signal.
[src:flexray/flexray] Single-cycle transmission errors may affect results near the boundary of the bits, but will not affect cycles in the middle of the 8-cycle region.
[src:flexray/flexray] The value of the bit is sampled in the middle of the 8-bit region.
[src:flexray/flexray] The errors are moved to the extreme cycles, and the clock is synchronized frequently enough for the drift to be small.
[src:flexray/flexray] All the communication is sent in the form of frames.
[src:flexray/flexray] If nothing is being communicated, the bus is held in state 1 (high voltage), so every receiver knows that the communication started when the voltage drops to 0.
[src:flexray/flexray] The receiver knows when the message is complete by checking whether BSS0 (1) or FES (0) was received.
[src:flexray/flexray] Note that 8-cycle per bit has nothing to do with bytes.
[src:flexray/flexray] 16 for BSS0 and BSS1 and 64 for its bits.
[src:flexray/flexray] Also note that BSS0 has value 1, and BSS1 has value 0.
[src:flexray/flexray] Clocks are resynchronized when the voted signal changes from 1 to 0, if the receiver was in either idle state or expecting BSS1.
[src:flexray/flexray] As synchronization is done on the voted signal, small transmission errors during synchronization that affect the boundary bits may skew the synchronization no more than 1 cycle.
[src:flexray/flexray] As there are at most 88 cycles between synchronization (BSS1, 8 bits of the last byte, FES and TES - 11 bits of 8 cycles each), and the clock drift is no larger than 1 per 300 cycles, the drift may skew the clock no more than 1 cycle.
[src:flexray/flexray] Small transmission errors during the receiving may affect only the boundary bits.
[src:flexray/flexray] So in the worst case the two middle bits are correct, and thus the sampled value is correct.
[src:flexray/flexray] Here's an example of a particularly bad case - error during synchronization, a lost cycle due to clock drift and error in transmission.
[src:flexray/flexray] Despite so many errors, the communication was received correctly.
[src:flexray/flexray] All except the first are synchronized by the 1->0 edge in the transmission fragment shown.
[src:flexray/flexray] When developing and/or troubleshooting the FlexRay bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:flexray/flexray] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools which collect, analyze, decode, store signals so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:flexray/flexray] Ethernet may replace FlexRay for bandwidth intensive, non-safety critical applications.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] TDMA is a type of time-division multiplexing (TDM), with the special point that instead of having one transmitter connected to one receiver, there are multiple transmitters.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] TDMA is used in digital 2G cellular systems such as Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM), IS-136, Personal Digital Cellular (PDC) and iDEN, in the Maritime Automatic Identification System, and in the Digital Enhanced Cordless Telecommunications (DECT) standard for portable phones.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] TDMA was first used in satellite communication systems by Western Union in its Westar 3 communications satellite in 1979.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] It is now used extensively in satellite communications, combat-net radio systems, and passive optical network (PON) networks for upstream traffic from premises to the operator.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] Most 2G cellular systems, with the notable exception of IS-95, are based on TDMA.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] GSM, D-AMPS, PDC, iDEN, and PHS are all examples of TDMA cellular systems.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] In the GSM system, the synchronization of the mobile phones is achieved by sending timing advance commands from the base station, which instruct the mobile phone to transmit earlier and by how much.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] This compensates for the speed-of-light propagation delay between phone and base station.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] The mobile phone is not allowed to transmit for its entire time slot; there is a guard interval at the end of each time slot.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] As the transmission moves into the guard period, the mobile network updates the timing advance to synchronize the transmission.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] Initial synchronization of a phone requires a special procedure.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] Before a mobile transmits, there is no way to know the timing advance required.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] For this reason, an entire time slot is dedicated to mobiles attempting to contact the network; this is known as the random-access channel (RACH) in GSM.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] The mobile transmits at the beginning of the time slot as received from the network.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] If the mobile is near the base station, the propagation delay is short and the initiation can succeed.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] If, however, the mobile phone is farther than 35 km from the base station, the delay will mean the mobile's transmission arrives at the end of the time slot.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] In this case, the mobile will be instructed to transmit its messages starting nearly a whole time slot earlier so that it can be received at the proper time.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] Finally, if the mobile is beyond the 35 km cell range of GSM, the transmission will arrive in a neighbouring time slot and be ignored.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] It is this feature, rather than limitations of power, that limits the range of a GSM cell to 35 km when no special extension techniques are used.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] By changing the synchronization between the uplink and downlink at the base station, however, this limitation can be overcome.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] UTRA-FDD (frequency division duplex) employs CDMA and FDD, where separate frequency bands are allocated for uplink and downlink transmissions.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] This separation minimizes interference and allows for continuous data transmission in both directions, making it suitable for environments with balanced traffic loads.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] UTRA-TDD (time division duplex), on the other hand, combines CDMA with TDMA and TDD.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] In this scheme, the same frequency band is used for both uplink and downlink, but at different times.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] This time-based separation is particularly advantageous in scenarios with asymmetric traffic loads, where the data rates for uplink and downlink differ significantly.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] By dynamically allocating time slots based on demand, UTRA-TDD can efficiently manage varying traffic patterns and enhance overall network capacity.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] The combination of these technologies in UMTS allows for more flexible and efficient use of the available spectrum, catering to diverse user demands and improving the adaptability of 3G networks to different operational environments.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] The ITU-T G.hn standard, which provides high-speed local area networking over existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables) is based on a TDMA scheme.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] In G.hn, a *master* device allocates *contention-free transmission opportunities* (CFTXOP) to other *slave* devices in the network.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] Only one device can use a CFTXOP at a time, thus avoiding collisions.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] FlexRay protocol, which is also a wired network used for safety-critical communication in modern cars, uses the TDMA method for data transmission control.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] In radio systems, TDMA is usually used alongside frequency-division multiple access (FDMA) and frequency-division duplex (FDD); the combination is referred to as FDMA/TDMA/FDD.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] This is the case in both GSM and IS-136, for example.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] Exceptions to this include the DECT and Personal Handy-phone System (PHS) micro-cellular systems, UMTS-TDD UMTS variant, and China's TD-SCDMA, which use time-division duplexing, where different time slots are allocated for the base station and handsets on the same frequency.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] A major advantage of TDMA is that the radio part of the mobile phone only needs to listen and broadcast for its own time slot.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] For the rest of the time, the mobile can carry out measurements on the network, detecting surrounding transmitters on different frequencies.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] This allows safe inter-frequency handovers, something which is difficult in CDMA systems, not supported at all in IS-95 and supported through complex system additions in Universal Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS).
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] This, in turn, allows for co-existence of microcell layers with macrocell layers.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] CDMA, by comparison, supports *soft hand-off*, which allows a mobile phone to be in communication with up to 6 base stations simultaneously, a type of *same-frequency handover*.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] The incoming packets are compared for quality, and the best one is selected.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] CDMA's *cell breathing* characteristic, where a terminal on the boundary of two congested cells will be unable to receive a clear signal, can often negate this advantage during peak periods.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] A disadvantage of TDMA systems is that they create interference at a frequency that is directly connected to the time slot length.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] This is the buzz that can sometimes be heard if a TDMA phone is left next to a radio or speakers.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] Another disadvantage is that the *dead time* between time slots limits the potential bandwidth of a TDMA channel.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] These are implemented in part because of the difficulty in ensuring that different terminals transmit at exactly the times required.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] Handsets that are moving will need to constantly adjust their timings to ensure their transmission is received at precisely the right time, because as they move further from the base station, their signal will take longer to arrive.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] This also means that the major TDMA systems have hard limits on cell sizes in terms of range, though in practice, the power levels required to receive and transmit over distances greater than the supported range would be mostly impractical anyway.
[src:flexray/time-division-multiple-access] In **dynamic time-division multiple access** (**dynamic TDMA**), a scheduling algorithm dynamically reserves a variable number of time slots in each frame to variable bit-rate data streams, based on the traffic demand of each data stream.
[src:flexray/time-triggered-architecture] Because they have highly deterministic timing behavior, TT systems have been used for many years to develop safety-critical aerospace and related systems.
[src:flexray/time-triggered-architecture] An early text that sets forth the principles of time triggered architecture, communications, and sparse time approaches is *Real-Time Systems: Design Principles for Distributed Embedded Applications* in 1997.
[src:flexray/time-triggered-architecture] Use of TT systems was popularized by the publication of *Patterns for Time-Triggered Embedded Systems* (PTTES) in 2001 and the related introductory book *Embedded C* in 2002.
[src:flexray/time-triggered-architecture] The PTTES book also introduced the concepts of time-triggered hybrid schedulers (an architecture for time-triggered systems that require task pre-emption) and shared-clock schedulers (an architecture for distributed time-triggered systems involving multiple, synchronized, nodes).
[src:flexray/time-triggered-architecture] Since publication of PTTES, extensive research work on TT systems has been carried out.
[src:flexray/time-triggered-architecture] Time-triggered systems are now commonly associated with international safety standards such as IEC 61508 (industrial systems), ISO 26262 (automotive systems), IEC 62304 (medical systems) and IEC 60730 (household goods).
[src:flexray/time-triggered-architecture] Time-triggered systems can be viewed as a subset of a more general event-triggered (ET) system architecture (see event-driven programming).
[src:flexray/time-triggered-architecture] Implementation of an ET system will typically involve use of multiple interrupts, each associated with specific periodic events (such as timer overflows) or aperiodic events (such as the arrival of messages over a communication bus at random points in time).
[src:flexray/time-triggered-architecture] ET designs are traditionally associated with the use of what is known as a real-time operating system (or RTOS), though use of such a software platform is not a defining characteristic of an ET architecture.
